        <h1>Introduction to Command Prompt (CMD)</h1>
        <p>The Command Prompt, often just called CMD, is a tool in Windows that lets you interact with your computer using text commands. It’s like talking to your computer directly using a special language. CMD can be very powerful and is useful for a variety of tasks, from navigating your files to running programs and scripts.</p>
        
        <h2>What is Command Prompt?</h2>
        <p>The Command Prompt is a program that lets you type in commands to perform various tasks on your computer. Instead of using the graphical interface with buttons and menus, you use text commands to control your computer. It’s like a virtual assistant that listens to your typed instructions.</p>
        
        <h2>Why Use CMD?</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Efficiency:</strong> CMD can be faster for some tasks compared to clicking through graphical interfaces.</li>
            <li><strong>Control:</strong> It provides more control over various system functions and tasks.</li>
            <li><strong>Automation:</strong> CMD is useful for automating repetitive tasks with scripts.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>Getting Started with CMD</h2>
        
        <h3>1. Opening Command Prompt</h3>
        <p>To open Command Prompt, follow these steps:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Search Method:</strong> Click on the Start menu or press the Windows key, then type "cmd" or "Command Prompt" and press Enter.</li>
            <li><strong>Run as Administrator:</strong> For some tasks, you might need elevated permissions. Right-click on "Command Prompt" in the search results and select "Run as administrator."</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h3>2. Basic Commands</h3>
        <p>Here are a few basic commands to get you started:</p>
        
        <div class="command">dir: Lists the files and folders in the current directory (folder).</div>
        <div class="command">cd foldername: Changes the directory. Use it to navigate to different folders.</div>
        <div class="command">mkdir newfolder: Creates a new directory (folder).</div>
        <div class="command">rmdir foldername: Removes a directory.</div>
        <div class="command">copy sourcefile destination: Copies files from one location to another.</div>
        <div class="command">del filename: Deletes a file.</div>
        
        <h3>3. Running Programs</h3>
        <p>You can run programs and scripts directly from CMD by typing their name. For example, to open Notepad, you can type:</p>
        <div class="command">notepad</div>
        
        <h3>4. Viewing Help</h3>
        <p>If you’re unsure about a command, you can get help by typing:</p>
        <div class="command">command /?</div>
        <p>For example, to get help about the <code>dir</code> command, type:</p>
        <div class="command">dir /?</div>
        
        <h3>5. Understanding Paths</h3>
        <p>When using CMD, you often need to specify paths to files and folders. Paths are the locations of these files or folders on your computer.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Absolute Path:</strong> The full path from the root of the drive, like <code>C:\Users\YourName\Documents</code>.</li>
            <li><strong>Relative Path:</strong> The path relative to your current location in CMD, like <code>Documents\file.txt</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2>Summary</h2>
        <p>Command Prompt is a powerful tool for interacting with your computer using text commands. It can help you manage files, run programs, and perform various tasks more efficiently. Here’s a quick recap:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Open CMD:</strong> Search for "cmd" or "Command Prompt."</li>
            <li><strong>Basic Commands:</strong> Use commands like <code>dir</code>, <code>cd</code>, <code>mkdir</code>, <code>copy</code>, and <code>del</code> to navigate and manage files.</li>
            <li><strong>Run Programs:</strong> Type the program’s name to run it.</li>
            <li><strong>Get Help:</strong> Use <code>command /?</code> to learn more about commands.</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>With these basics, you’re ready to start exploring CMD and using it to make your computer work the way you want!</p>
